-size:10pt"> the impact of inspections on the quality of education in schools and whether inspections contribute to enhancing the main indicators of school improvement.  The present limited conception of accountability should be reformulated to emphasise the reciproca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">l and inter-dependent nature of responsibilities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  All maintained schools should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">covered by the same approach to inspection, whether academy status or not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:22.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The accountability of policy-makers at national level should be examined by regular publication </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of indicators of ‘stakeholders’ confidence.  Currently, confidence levels in Ofsted should be a significant cause for concern for the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> members of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Education Select Committee.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:22.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">YouGov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> poll</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-fam