/span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">generate working time </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and bureaucratic burdens </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">for teachers that do not ultimately benefit pupils.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:22.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In a recent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">NUT </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">survey</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of 300 schools who have been inspected under the current Ofsted framework, teachers expressed the views below</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:26.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Only seven per cent concluded that inspections supported school improvement, whereas 48 per cent said it did not, and 45 per cent expressed ‘mix</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ed views’.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:26.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Eighty-three per cent of teachers said the inspection had created </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">significant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> additional workload for them.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:26.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ninety per cent of teachers reported the inspection had generated additional pressure and stress for them.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:26.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A third of schools (29%) re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ported that they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">agreed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> inspection had disrupted activities for pupils and a further 20 per cent of schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">agreed strongly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that inspection was disruptive.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:26.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Not a single teacher indicated the inspection was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">supportive or motivated teachers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> (although one in five indicated ‘mixed views</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:22.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The NUT survey</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of schools recently inspected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> revealed that in almost one in three schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“the inspection was stressful for staff as the school felt under attack”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.  This cannot be the right climate for engendering dialogue with qualified professionals about their practice in the classroom.  This punitive approach to school inspection cannot be justified and is counter-productive.  Professional dialogue cannot be co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nducted in a climate of fear, suspicion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> mistrust.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:22.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">If a school inspection system is maintained, teachers and parents equally expect such a system to contribute to school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.  It does not justify tax-payer investment if this cannot be demonstrat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ed.  In the NUT survey, only 28 per cent believed the recommendations for improvement in the inspection report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> for their school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> would help </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">their school progress.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:22.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Some of the quotes below are typical:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 36pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“The recent Ofsted experience was unjust and it was cl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">ear to all involved that the result was pre-decided and that the inspectors were drawing conclusions about the school to fit historical data and meet the government agenda.  There is not a member of staff or parent at the school who agrees with the result </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">given by Ofsted or what is said in the report.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 36pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 36pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“It confirmed what I thought about Ofsted.  The criteria they judge a school on is so specific and focused on evidence provided by SLT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> [senior leadership team]</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> that they do not notice anything else going on.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">  This just encourages SLT to spend more time on Ofsted evidence and less time on running the school.  A sad state of affairs.  Ofsted serves no useful purpose to education and should be abolished.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 36pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 36pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“We are due now and the pressure is so great it is makin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">g me ill.  I am considering leaving because of it.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 36pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 36pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“Context of the school needs to be taken into account.  We as a profession have little faith that the Ofsted process is anything but a tool for political manipulation, especially in the insane rush for A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">cademy status.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 36pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 36pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“The inspection judgements and comments did not tell the school anything that they didn’t already know.  Comments as the inspectors left which stated they could see that the ethos of the school was outstanding as they entered the school, b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">ut couldn’t comment on this, were not helpful in helping the school feel that inspection is broadly based and not just on data.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 36pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 36pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">The lead inspector was a Cllr with no teaching qualification or experience.  Second inspector seemed to know nothing about pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">imary education and gave feedback on a maths lesson when in fact he had observed a literacy lesson.  Teachers were downgraded for allowing children to drink water during a PE lesson.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.9pt; padding-left:17.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The NUT considers that the Select Committee should recommend that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:26.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">school self-evaluation, which should be central in any national approach to school improvement, is a missing component in the current system;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:26.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">accountability and self-improvement should be seen as two strands of the one inter-related strategy;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:26.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">provisi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">on of time and resources </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">must</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> feature as a key issue in school improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and schools must collaborate within an overall framework for a public education service, not compete</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">; and</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:26.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">school inspection is only a valuable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">element</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of the Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">vision fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">r school improvement if Ofsted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">earns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the trust and respect of the profession and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">schools have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> confidence in Ofsted judgements and recommendations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">              </span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> NUT commissioned a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">YouGov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> poll of 826 teachers, December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> NUT survey of over 300 schools inspected under current framework, November 2013</span></p></body></html>